Halve, peel and thinly slice the @echalion shallot{1}(halved, peeled and thinly sliced). Trim the @carrot{1}(trimmed). Grate the carrot on the coarse side of your #grater{}.

Bring the @water{300%ml} to the boil in a large #saucepan{} over high heat. Once boiling, add the @cinnamon stick{1} and half the @chicken stock powder{1%tbsp}. Stir to dissolve the stock powder. Add the @basmati rice{150%g} and pop a #lid{} on the pan. Lower the heat to medium. Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, heat a glug of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} over high heat. Add the @British beef mince{240%g} and cook until browned, ~{5-6%minutes}. Break up with a #wooden spoon{} whilst cooking. Drain off any excess fat and then add the shallot, carrot, @ground coriander{1%tsp}, @smoked paprika{1%tsp} and @ground cumin{2%tsp} and stir. Reduce the heat and cook until the veggies have softened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Stir in the @chopped tomatoes{1}(finely chopped) and the @water{200%ml}. Bring to the boil and add the remaining stock powder, stir to dissolve. Lower the heat so as the sauce is gently bubbling away. Cook until the sauce has thickened and reduced by half, ~{15-20%minutes}. Stir in the @baby spinach{125%g} one handful at a time until wilted.

Pick the @mint{1}(leaves picked from stalks and roughly chopped) and roughly chop (discard the stalks). Mix half the mint with the @Greek style natural yoghurt{150%g}.

Remove the cinnamon stick from the rice and fluff it up with a #fork{}. Share between your #bowls{}. Add some @salt{} and @black pepper{} to the beef keema to taste if necessary. Spoon it over the rice and finish with the minty yoghurt and a sprinkling of remaining mint leaves. Enjoy!

